South Korea, India, Thailand, Japan, China: Asia Bond and Currency Preview

-- B y   V .   R a m a k r i s h n a n
-- 
2011-05-12T22:46:38Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-12/south-korea-india-thailand-japan-china-asia-bond-and-currency-preview.html
The following events and economic
reports may influence trading in  Asia ’s bonds and currencies
today. Bond yields and exchange rates are from the previous
trading session unless stated otherwise.  Japan: Chief Cabinet Secretary Yukio Edano and Finance
Minister  Yoshihiko Noda  will hold media briefings after a
Cabinet meeting in the morning. Edano will have another press
briefing at 4 p.m. in  Tokyo .  The yield on the 1.3 percent government bond due March 2021
was 1.11 percent, according to Japan Bond Trading Co., the
nation’s largest interdealer debt broker.  The yen traded at 81.00 per dollar at 7:42 a.m. in Tokyo.  China : The government will sell 20 billion yuan ($3.1
billion) of one-year bonds and 10 billion yuan of 182-day bills
today.  The yield on the 3.83 percent bond due March 2021 was 3.83
percent, according to Chinabond, the nation’s biggest debt-
clearing house. The yuan was at 6.5000.  India : The finance ministry will sell 120 billion rupees
($2.7 billion) of bonds due in 2018, 2021 and 2040 today.  The yield on the 7.80 percent bond due April 2021 was 8.23
percent. The rupee was at 44.9700.  South Korea : The central bank will increase the seven-day
repo rate by 0.25 percentage point to 3.25 percent, according to
12 of 14 economists in a Bloomberg survey before a policy review
today. Two forecast the rate to remain unchanged.  The yield on South Korea’s 3.75 percent bond due June 2013
was 3.15 percent. The won was at 1,085.15 per dollar.  Thailand: The central bank will release foreign-exchange
reserve data for the week ended May 6. The reserves rose 0.6
percent to $189.9 billion the previous week.  The Bank of  Thailand  will sell a combined 137 billion baht
($4.5 billion) of 12-, 28-, 91- and 182-day bills and 12 billion
baht of bonds due 2014.  The yield on the 3.125 percent debt due December 2015 was
3.44 percent. The baht was at 30.32 per dollar.  To contact the reporter on this story:
